HEADWORD: Indulto
<hw>In*dul"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
}</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>indultum</ets> indulgence, favor,
fr. <ets>indultus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>indulgere</ets>: cf. It.
<ets>indulto</ets>, F. <ets>indult</ets>. See
<er>Indulge</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A privilege or exemption; an indulgence; a
dispensation granted by the pope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Spain)</fld> <def>A duty levied on all
importations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indument</ent>⟦br⟧
